she had an affair.

16:55.516 --> 16:57.818
Can we please
go home?

16:57.884 --> 17:01.354
I was completely blindsided.

17:01.422 --> 17:05.726
* You told me *

17:05.792 --> 17:08.228
* That you would leave me *

17:08.294 --> 17:10.130
* Here in tears *

17:12.866 --> 17:16.403
* Now you're gone
and hours seem like years *

17:16.470 --> 17:19.473
Nothing in my life had
prepared me for that moment.

17:19.540 --> 17:22.809
I was just
absolutely devastated.

17:22.876 --> 17:25.546
It may be difficult
to imagine,

17:25.612 --> 17:30.250
related to the publisher
of Playboy magazine.

17:30.316 --> 17:34.588
But I had been intimate with
only one woman in my life,

17:34.655 --> 17:36.757
the woman I was gonna marry.

17:36.823 --> 17:39.426
How I dealt with it,
I don't really know.

17:39.493 --> 17:42.262
I just dealt with it by,
I think somehow,

17:42.328 --> 17:43.864
putting it out of my mind.

17:43.930 --> 17:47.501
* Where did you go *

17:47.568 --> 17:50.937
This was,
after all, the 1950s.

17:51.004 --> 17:55.542
And back then, you married
the girl you were in love with,

17:55.609 --> 17:57.844
no matter what.

17:57.911 --> 18:02.516
And, truth be told, I was
still in love with Millie.

18:02.583 --> 18:05.018
* Johnny *

18:05.085 --> 18:06.953
* Johnny, you're too young *

18:07.020 --> 18:09.456
* But I'm gonna
get married *

18:09.523 --> 18:11.191
* You're so young *

18:11.257 --> 18:13.927
* My name she'll carry *

18:13.994 --> 18:16.497
Our wedding
was in the summer of '49.

18:16.563 --> 18:18.164
* Johnny, you're so smart *

18:18.231 --> 18:22.302
We had our
whole lives ahead of us.

18:22.368 --> 18:25.138
And in January of 1951...

18:25.205 --> 18:26.239
That's great news.

18:26.306 --> 18:28.742
...I landed my dream job.

18:28.809 --> 18:31.211
I'd just be writing copy
in the ad department,

18:31.277 --> 18:34.014
but I'd be working for
my favorite magazine...

18:34.080 --> 18:35.516
* It sets my soul on fire *

18:35.582 --> 18:37.984
...Esquire.

18:38.051 --> 18:40.086
* How come every time
she leave me *

18:40.153 --> 18:42.856
This was my chance to do
something creative.

18:42.923 --> 18:45.692
* ...too young to marry *

18:45.759 --> 18:48.729
* But not to hide
an aching heart *

18:52.699 --> 18:54.568
But I quickly realized

18:54.635 --> 18:57.804
it wasn't what I'd imagined.

18:57.871 --> 18:59.740
Esquire had changed.

18:59.806 --> 19:03.844
The 1950's was kind of
a down period for Esquire.

19:03.910 --> 19:05.612
I think they were
probably reeling

19:05.679 --> 19:07.681
from the end of World War II

19:07.748 --> 19:10.216
and the beginnings
of a more repressive society

19:10.283 --> 19:12.485
and probably tended toward being
a little more conservative.

19:12.553 --> 19:15.121
They'd moved away
from all the things

19:15.188 --> 19:17.524
I'd been drawn to
growing up.

19:17.591 --> 19:20.126
The full-page cartoons,
the jokes,

19:20.193 --> 19:22.829
and most of all,
the pin-up girls.

19:25.131 --> 19:28.769
The job turned out to be
a huge disappointment.

19:28.835 --> 19:30.571
And when they
refused my request

19:30.637 --> 19:34.007
for a five dollar raise...

19:34.074 --> 19:35.175
I quit.

19:37.644 --> 19:41.481
But everything changed
in 1952...

19:41.548 --> 19:42.983
* You couldn't be cuter *

19:43.049 --> 19:44.585
...when Millie gave birth

19:44.651 --> 19:46.086
to our first child.

19:46.152 --> 19:47.788
* Plus that
intelligent face *

19:47.854 --> 19:50.390
We named her Christie.

19:50.456 --> 19:53.226
* ...charm for me *

19:53.293 --> 19:55.395
And while I loved
being a father...

19:55.461 --> 19:57.998
suddenly, I had a family
to provide for.

19:58.064 --> 19:59.933
* You are the little
grand slam *

20:00.000 --> 20:02.903
* I'll bring to my family *

20:02.969 --> 20:06.172
And I needed to find a job...

20:07.808 --> 20:10.877
...any job...
as quickly as possible.

20:21.221 --> 20:25.391
So I took a low-level position
at a publishing house...

20:25.458 --> 20:29.129
crunching numbers
and trying to improve sales.

20:29.195 --> 20:33.834
But the job was about
as mind-numbing as it gets.

20:40.506 --> 20:42.876
And, as time went on...

20:44.177 --> 20:47.948
I realized I'd become
just one of the masses.

20:50.083 --> 20:54.988
The 1950's was a time
of conformity.

20:55.055 --> 20:58.091
The course was set out...
you went to school,

20:58.158 --> 21:00.060
you got married,
you had children,

21:00.126 --> 21:04.765
you got the best job you could
to support your family.

21:04.831 --> 21:08.702
There was not a lot of room
for individuality,

21:08.769 --> 21:12.238
and that did not
appeal to Hef at all.

21:30.323 --> 21:33.259
I only went into that bar
to be alone.

21:36.062 --> 21:38.965
* Just one look *

21:39.032 --> 21:43.737
* And I fell so hard *

21:43.804 --> 21:45.672
And I certainly
wasn't expecting

21:45.739 --> 21:47.140
what happened next.

21:48.909 --> 21:51.544
* With you *

21:51.611 --> 21:53.947
* Oh oh, oh oh *

21:54.014 --> 21:56.683
* I found out *

21:56.750 --> 22:02.188
* How good it feels *

22:02.255 --> 22:03.890
* To have... *

22:03.957 --> 22:06.192
I knew what I was doing
was wrong...

22:06.259 --> 22:11.898
but for the first time
in a long time, I felt alive.

22:28.514 --> 22:32.753
The affair ended
as quickly as it started.

22:32.819 --> 22:34.821
But it sparked
something in me.

22:38.258 --> 22:41.527
I'd always been happiest
being creative,

22:41.594 --> 22:45.098
and as I looked back on
my cartoons, short stories,

22:45.165 --> 22:48.068
and articles
from Shaft magazine,

22:48.134 --> 22:50.636
I saw what I was missing.

22:50.703 --> 22:52.438
I became convinced very early

22:52.505 --> 22:55.475
that older people
became cynical

22:55.541 --> 22:57.744
and somehow
sold out those dreams.

22:57.811 --> 23:00.146
And that's what
I was unwilling to do.

23:00.213 --> 23:02.749
I was not willing
to make that tradeoff,

23:02.816 --> 23:06.619
to get in line
and lock step march away

23:06.686 --> 23:08.922
the rest of my life.

23:08.989 --> 23:11.691
My father was still
trying to find himself,

23:11.758 --> 23:13.259
and had a number of jobs

23:13.326 --> 23:15.361
that I think were
less than satisfying.

23:15.428 --> 23:19.966
He was always, I think, drawn
to both visual expression

23:20.033 --> 23:23.503
and also to big ideas.

23:25.371 --> 23:28.008
It was then that
I made a decision

23:28.074 --> 23:31.411
that would change the course
of my life forever.

23:40.020 --> 23:43.990
I decided to create
a magazine of my own.

23:48.228 --> 23:51.397
One that would appeal
to guys like me...

23:51.464 --> 23:56.102
featuring articles about music,
literature, art, and culture.

23:57.603 --> 23:59.940
When he started the magazine,

24:00.006 --> 24:03.676
he actually created
the magazine for himself.

24:03.743 --> 24:06.046
There was no magazine
out there

24:06.112 --> 24:10.917
that he found
of interest for a young guy.

24:11.952 --> 24:13.854
Most of the men's magazines

24:13.920 --> 24:16.489
were hunting and fishing
magazines,

24:16.556 --> 24:21.895
gun magazines,
not sophisticated magazines.

24:21.962 --> 24:23.329
The only
sophisticated magazine

24:23.396 --> 24:26.366
that was out there
at the time was Esquire.

24:28.935 --> 24:32.772
It was going to be, uh,
what Esquire used to be.

24:32.839 --> 24:34.074
And it was a magazine

24:34.140 --> 24:36.376
that would really be
for the young urban male.

24:36.442 --> 24:42.082
But my magazine
would be so much more.

24:42.148 --> 24:44.217
In the same way
that Kinsey blew the cover

24:44.284 --> 24:47.120
off sexuality in America...

24:47.187 --> 24:48.955
I wanted my magazine

24:49.022 --> 24:52.758
to confront
the topic of sex head on.

24:52.825 --> 24:55.395
For Hef, I think
the message about sex

24:55.461 --> 24:58.364
has always been
that it's healthy.

24:58.431 --> 25:00.200
And natural.

25:00.266 --> 25:02.202
And, that we shouldn't
be ashamed of it.

25:02.268 --> 25:04.404
And we should embrace it.

25:04.470 --> 25:08.141
That was not the popular
opinion in the 1950s.

25:08.208 --> 25:09.742
And it's hard to remember now,

25:09.809 --> 25:14.247
when you look back, that this
was fairly revolutionary.

25:19.785 --> 25:22.923
It was one thing
to talk about sex,

25:22.989 --> 25:25.291
but I wanted to do more

25:28.761 --> 25:31.764
Growing up, my favorite
parts of Esquire

25:31.831 --> 25:34.400
were those drawings
of the pin-up girls.

25:36.702 --> 25:40.506
But I thought my magazine
could go one step further...

25:40.573 --> 25:43.509
by showing photos
of nude women.

25:43.576 --> 25:46.146
I think the brilliance
of the magazine was

25:46.212 --> 25:49.049
it spoke to all the interests
of young men.

25:49.115 --> 25:52.118
So those were
cultural and political.

25:52.185 --> 25:54.720
It was fashion,
it was travel.

25:54.787 --> 25:58.925
But it also was an unabashed
recognition of the interest

25:58.992 --> 26:02.262
that young men had
in beautiful women.

26:02.328 --> 26:05.665
I knew that there
would be nothing that was

26:05.731 --> 26:07.968
outside,
uh, the boundaries

26:08.034 --> 26:10.203
of what was already
being published.

26:10.270 --> 26:12.138
In other words,
there were magazines,

26:12.205 --> 26:15.008
art photography magazines,
sunbathing magazines,

26:15.075 --> 26:17.143
with nudes in them.

26:17.210 --> 26:20.746
I wanted to package it
in a way that...

26:20.813 --> 26:23.984
suggested that this
was not art.

26:24.050 --> 26:28.188
It was... something
with an editorial message,

26:28.254 --> 26:30.623
and the editorial message
was that sex was okay.

26:34.995 --> 26:37.563
I was going to combine
a modern lifestyle magazine

26:37.630 --> 26:39.699
with nude photos
of women.

26:42.702 --> 26:45.038
And I had
the perfect name for it.

26:48.941 --> 26:51.011
Stag Party.

26:53.446 --> 26:55.881
What magazines do you read?

26:55.948 --> 26:58.518
Why?

26:58.584 --> 27:00.453
Just name some.

27:00.520 --> 27:01.721
I-- I don't know.

27:01.787 --> 27:03.589
I knew
I liked the idea...

27:03.656 --> 27:06.026
Now I just needed to see
if anyone else would, too.

27:06.092 --> 27:07.660
And the first guy
that I thought of

27:07.727 --> 27:10.330
was my old friend
Eldon Sellers.

27:10.396 --> 27:12.165
What if there
was a magazine

27:12.232 --> 27:15.401
that didn't fall
into any one category?

27:15.468 --> 27:16.936
That took all
your favorite things

27:17.003 --> 27:19.305
and put them
into one place.

27:19.372 --> 27:21.974
And it'll have
a full-page color photo

27:22.042 --> 27:24.077
of a real life
pin-up girl...

27:24.144 --> 27:27.113
completely nude.

27:31.884 --> 27:32.985
It's gonna be great,
Eldon.

27:33.053 --> 27:34.620
It sounds like it.

27:34.687 --> 27:36.922
It's going to be
a progressive magazine for men.

27:36.989 --> 27:39.959
He came to me and said that he
would like to have some help

27:40.026 --> 27:43.296
raising some money
for a magazine.

27:43.363 --> 27:47.100
He did a terrific job
of promoting the idea

27:47.167 --> 27:48.701
and explaining it,
and he was...

27:48.768 --> 27:50.936
he was extremely
articulate about that.

27:51.003 --> 27:52.238
I like that.

27:52.305 --> 27:54.140
Eldon liked it so much,

27:54.207 --> 27:56.509
he chipped in $2,000

27:56.576 --> 27:59.912
and even offered to help me
find more investors.

27:59.979 --> 28:03.416
And, honestly, I was going to
need all the help I could get.

28:05.051 --> 28:07.987
Just to give you a sense of how
much money I needed to raise,

28:08.054 --> 28:11.757
Time magazine was started
with an initial investment

28:11.824 --> 28:14.294
of $86,000.

28:14.360 --> 28:17.863
And that was all the way
back in 1923.

28:17.930 --> 28:22.735
Today, that's the equivalent
of over $1.2 million.

28:22.802 --> 28:24.537
Even when Playboy was started,

28:24.604 --> 28:28.074
it was unusual to have
that little capital

28:28.141 --> 28:31.244
and those few resources.

28:31.311 --> 28:34.647
Today, it would be almost
impossible to consider

28:34.714 --> 28:38.451
starting a magazine
without having millions
and millions of dollars

28:38.518 --> 28:42.122
and the capacity
to sustain losses for three,

28:42.188 --> 28:44.257
four, five, six years.

28:47.860 --> 28:50.696
* My man called me
this morning... *

28:50.763 --> 28:52.932
I figured
after Eldon's investment,

28:52.998 --> 28:56.001
I was still going to need
at least $6,000

28:56.068 --> 28:58.037
to get my idea off the ground.

28:58.104 --> 29:00.005
* Said hello, baby *

29:00.072 --> 29:03.743
So we started meeting
with investors in Chicago.

29:03.809 --> 29:05.645
What do you think?

29:05.711 --> 29:07.347
A lot of them said no.

29:07.413 --> 29:11.417
* My head went
round and round, yeah *

29:11.484 --> 29:14.554
But a few of them said yes.

29:14.620 --> 29:15.921
* My man called me
this morning *

29:15.988 --> 29:18.291
Hello, Fred?
Hugh Hefner here.

29:18.358 --> 29:20.460
Well, I'm happy
you asked.

29:20.526 --> 29:21.794
Okay...

29:21.861 --> 29:23.363
I was hoping for
slightly better than that,

29:23.429 --> 29:25.165
to be honest with you.

29:25.231 --> 29:27.567
Okay...
that sounds great.

29:27.633 --> 29:29.135
No matter what,

29:29.202 --> 29:31.637
I was going
to make this happen.

29:31.704 --> 29:33.873
And, after weeks
of calling...

29:33.939 --> 29:36.409
we got my younger brother,
Keith,

29:36.476 --> 29:38.944
and my neighbors
to pitch in.

29:39.011 --> 29:42.948
Even my puritanical mother
gave me $1,000.

29:43.015 --> 29:45.485
I never had a long conversation
with my grandmother

29:45.551 --> 29:47.287
about her investment
in the magazine,

29:47.353 --> 29:49.689
but, knowing her as I did,

29:49.755 --> 29:52.024
I would say that...
she would have said

29:52.091 --> 29:54.560
it was not a magazine for her,

29:54.627 --> 29:56.596
but that she
believed in her son.

29:56.662 --> 29:59.165
But even
with my family and friends

29:59.232 --> 30:00.766
pitching in,

30:00.833 --> 30:03.503
I was still
about $600 short.

30:03.569 --> 30:05.171
So, out of desperation,

30:05.238 --> 30:08.608
I put my furniture in hock.

30:08.674 --> 30:10.643
It included some pretty nice
pieces by designers

30:10.710 --> 30:13.213
like Herman Miller and Eames.

30:13.279 --> 30:16.516
* My man called me
this morning, stop **

30:16.582 --> 30:19.419
And finally,
I hit my goal.

30:27.327 --> 30:29.595
With the money
finally in place,

30:29.662 --> 30:32.398
I was ready to start
making my magazine.

30:34.467 --> 30:36.436
But I quickly realized

30:36.502 --> 30:38.838
I couldn't do this
on my own.

30:42.942 --> 30:45.177
So... what
did Frank tell you?

30:45.245 --> 30:46.679
Well, not much.

30:46.746 --> 30:48.681
Just that you're...
you're starting a magazine,

30:48.748 --> 30:50.483
and you might be looking
for an art director.

30:50.550 --> 30:52.585
Well it's not just
any magazine.

30:52.652 --> 30:56.021
It's a lifestyle magazine
with a full-color

30:56.088 --> 30:59.325
nude spread
of a girl in each issue.

30:59.392 --> 31:01.727
But I want this magazine
to be more than that.

31:01.794 --> 31:05.398
A look that nobody
has ever seen before.

31:05.465 --> 31:09.302
I want this magazine
to be beautiful.

31:09.369 --> 31:11.704
You want to do a magazine
with nude girls,

31:11.771 --> 31:14.039
and you want the magazine
to be beautiful?

31:16.276 --> 31:17.777
That's right.

31:19.512 --> 31:22.648
I had my art director...

31:22.715 --> 31:24.216
a popular graphic designer

31:24.284 --> 31:26.919
from the Southside
of Chicago...

31:26.986 --> 31:28.654
named Art Paul.

31:33.493 --> 31:36.996
Art Paul was ahead of his time.

31:39.198 --> 31:41.901
His designs were modern

31:41.967 --> 31:45.505
and different from Esquire, and
that's what Hef was looking for.

31:45.571 --> 31:49.575
And Hef has a knack
for finding that talent.

31:54.079 --> 31:57.583
With Art Paul
on board, I had my team.

31:57.650 --> 31:59.519
I'd write the copy,

31:59.585 --> 32:02.388
Art would create the design...

32:02.455 --> 32:05.090
and Eldon would
handle promotions.

32:05.157 --> 32:08.928
My small apartment became
Stag Party's offices...

32:08.994 --> 32:11.664
and it was finally
time to get to work.

32:13.466 --> 32:15.000
Playboy was never

32:15.067 --> 32:16.469
a corporate magazine.

32:16.536 --> 32:18.203
It was never part of
a giant publishing house.

32:18.270 --> 32:21.874
You're talking about a magazine
that is as DIY as it gets.

32:21.941 --> 32:26.946
It's one man started it
at his kitchen table in Chicago.

32:27.012 --> 32:29.815
We came up
with countless ideas

32:29.882 --> 32:31.984
for how to make
the magazine stand out.

32:34.754 --> 32:40.526
At that time, 3-D movies
were hugely popular...

32:40.593 --> 32:44.697
so we considered featuring
our girls in 3-D.

32:44.764 --> 32:47.232
But attaching a pair
of glasses to every issue

32:47.299 --> 32:50.670
proved too expensive.

32:50.736 --> 32:55.007
In the end, we realized it
wasn't about the gimmick.

32:55.074 --> 32:58.911
We just needed to find
the perfect girl.

32:58.978 --> 33:01.814
* Hurry on down to my house,
baby, ain't anybody home... *

33:01.881 --> 33:03.449
In the 1950s,

33:03.516 --> 33:05.818
if you wanted
a nude photo of a model,

33:05.885 --> 33:09.389
and you didn't have
your own to photograph...

33:09.455 --> 33:11.691
the only places
you could get them from

33:11.757 --> 33:13.893
were calendar companies.

33:13.959 --> 33:16.328
And, for a price,
you could purchase

33:16.396 --> 33:17.797
the rights to their pin-ups.

33:17.863 --> 33:20.800
* Ain't nobody home
but me *

33:20.866 --> 33:24.069
We reached out
to countless calendar companies

33:24.136 --> 33:26.038
and gathered
hundreds of options

33:26.105 --> 33:27.640
for our first cover girl.

33:27.707 --> 33:30.976
* There's nobody home
but me **

33:31.043 --> 33:33.012
What about her, huh?

33:34.914 --> 33:36.449
No, she's not right.

33:38.183 --> 33:39.485
This one?

33:41.053 --> 33:42.622
No, no.

33:46.492 --> 33:48.027
Maybe if you
tell me exactly what

33:48.093 --> 33:49.562
you're looking for,
we can find the girl.

33:49.629 --> 33:51.063
Well,
that's the problem.

33:51.130 --> 33:53.533
We're not looking for a girl,
we're looking for the girl.

33:53.599 --> 33:55.100
What does that mean?

33:55.167 --> 33:57.169
We need to find a girl that
no guy would be able to resist.

33:57.236 --> 33:59.304
Someone who will
make it impossible

33:59.371 --> 34:01.173
for a guy not to open
the cover.

34:01.240 --> 34:02.508
Oh, well, if that's all...

34:02.575 --> 34:04.877
I don't know where she is,
but she's not here.

34:18.424 --> 34:22.061
I'd spent weeks
looking for a cover girl...

34:22.127 --> 34:24.464
and I was starting
to lose hope.

34:27.500 --> 34:30.202
But in the fall of 1953,

34:30.269 --> 34:33.806
the solution would
come out of nowhere.

34:38.310 --> 34:40.946
* I touch your lips
and all at once *

34:41.013 --> 34:43.415
* The sparks go flying *

34:43.483 --> 34:48.153
* Those devil that know
so well the art of lying *

34:48.220 --> 34:50.656
* And though I see
the danger still... *

34:50.723 --> 34:52.224
In those days,

34:52.291 --> 34:55.661
Marilyn Monroe was every man's
ultimate fantasy.

34:55.728 --> 34:58.030
* ...your kiss of fire *

34:58.097 --> 35:00.399
* Just like a torch
you set the soul... *

35:00.466 --> 35:02.902
She was the very
pinnacle of sexuality.

35:02.968 --> 35:05.905
* I must go on
